      "finding": "Source and target systems, the end-to-end ordered data flow, the transformation stage and platform, source purge, and a regulatory retention requirement are all clearly specified. However, the data-movement design has gaps: (1) lineage is only minimally addressed via a single audit-metadata step rather than end-to-end capture; (2) retention is stated as a requirement (YE+7 / 10-year) but is not bound to specific raw (ADLS Gen2) vs. derived (Snowflake) datasets, and the source-purge step is not explicitly gated on that retention period; and (3) no data-quality, reconciliation, or late-arriving/duplicate handling between source and target is described.",
      "reasoning": "Source & Target Systems: Dataverse (system of record) and Snowflake (archival/reporting destination) are explicitly named with a clear leave/land boundary, satisfying that requirement. Data Flow: Section 4.1 and 4.2 give an ordered, reproducible extract->stage->transform->load sequence (Dynamics/Dataverse -> ADF -> ADLS Gen2 -> Databricks -> Snowflake), and the movement mechanism (ADF Pipeline) is named, satisfying Data Flow. Transformation: 'Transform data in Databricks' names both the step and the platform, and raw (ADLS Gen2) vs. transformed (Snowflake) data are distinguishable, satisfying Transformation. Lineage: only 'Record audit metadata' is present at a single step rather than end-to-end lineage at each stage, so lineage is partial and must be flagged as a gap. Retention: YE+7 and 10-year retention are required, but the guideline requires a retention period defined for BOTH raw and derived data within the design; the SAD ties retention to neither ADLS nor Snowflake specifically, and Step 7 'Purge archived records from Dataverse' is not explicitly conditioned on the retention period, so deletion-consistent-with-retention is unverified. Data Quality & Reconciliation: no reconciliation frequency/ownership or late-arriving/duplicate handling is described anywhere in the assigned sections.",
